msDesc.head: New Testament, prefaced by illustrated cycle of the Life of Christ

summary.p: This volume is a composite of elements drawn from two originally separate manuscripts, one perhaps made at Bury St Edmunds, the other given to Bury in the fourteenth century.

Part I comprises six leaves bearing a cycle of thirty-nine outline drawings of scenes from the New Testament, drawn by an artist whose style derives closely from that of the Alexis Master, the artist of the St Albans Psalter (Hildesheim, Pfarrbibliothek, St Godehard, MS 1) and other St Albans books (e.g. Cambridge, King's College, MS 19), whose work has been shown to have been of fundamental importance for the diffusion of a new style of Romanesque art in England. A Bury origin for the leaves has been suggested since the style of the Alexis Master was known at Bury: a very close follower illustrated a Life of St Edmund (New York, Pierpont Morgan Library, M. 736), presumably at Bury, since the text is in the hand of a Bury scribe. The underdrawings of the Life may have been the work of the Alexis Master himself. Furthermore, the first three leaves were subsequently tinted by another less competent artist, whose colouring in the borders may reflects the influence of the Bury Bible (Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 2), certainly produced at and for the Abbey.

The iconography corresponds in many respects to the cycle of pictures that prefaces the St Albans Psalter, and the more extensive cycle that once prefaced the Eadwine Psalter (Cambridge, Trinity College, MS R.17.1). Some of the iconography, however, is more unusual, and displays a close relationship with Ottonian picture traditions, most especially those in eleventh-century manuscripts from Echternach, near Trier (an influence also detectable, though to a lesser extent, in the Eadwine picture cycle).

The leaves probably formed, or were intended to form, part of a larger manuscript, but it is not wholly clear what type of book this might have been, although a strong case can be made that they were intended to accompany the second element, a copy of the New Testament, from the outset. Surviving manuscripts suggest that biblical picture cycles normally accompanied Psalters, yet the proportion of the Bury leaves are much larger than those of twelfth-century Psalters (apart from the Eadwine Psalter, which is exceptional), and are more typical of the large format Romanesque Bibles, such as the Bury Bible and Dover Bible (Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 3-4). The absence of any Old Testament scenes is also anomalous.

The second element is a copy of the New Testament, also produced during the second quarter or mid-twelfth century by a single expert scribe who identifies himself as William in a colophon on f. 182v. Major divisions of the text are marked with initials in rich body-colour and gold; five are historiated and the remainder ornamented with tight foliage spirals, monsters, birds and human figures. A second level of textual division is indicated with flat-colour 'arabesque' initials. The script is unlike that of numerous surviving books produced at Bury St Edmunds during the mid-twelfth century, neither do the arabesque initials contain any of the motifs typical of Bury decoration of this date. It is especially notable for the iconography of its Evangelist portraits, in particular that of Mark, which E. Parker McLachlan believes to be unique in manuscript art of the twelfth century and earlier in depicting him as a tetramorph. His lion-symbol surmounts a seated human body with three further heads comprising the symbols of the other three Evangelists. The figure is shown turning to his left and cutting off his thumb, an act attributed to Mark in the prologue that accompanies the Gospel. Other aspects of the style and iconography of the major initials can be paralleled in English Romanesque manuscripts but without shedding light on a possible place of origin. It had been assumed that this part of the manuscript only came to Bury in the fourteenth century, as the gift of the sacrist, Reginald of Denham, however it has subsequently been observed the inscription on f. 7r recording his donation could also be interpreted as recording his role in redeeming the book following its possible use as a pledge. Such an interpretation, together with the physical evidence of the dimensions of the ruling of the miniature leaves and their sewing, allow for the possibility that the two parts of the manuscript were bound together, and at Bury, from the outset.

Professor Tessa Webber
Professor of Palaeography, Faculty of History
University of Cambridge

collation.note: First and least leaves are pastedowns.

note.p: On the front pastedown, in a rough anglicana hand of s. xv, are eighteen lines from Stans puer ad mensam, ascribed to John Lydgate Lydgate, John, 1370?-1451? (DIMEV 3888; IMEV 2233).
On the front pastedown, the names only for a T-O map of the world, s. xiv, probably a pen-trial.

binding.p: Stoakley, 1946, repaired by Douglas Cockerell Cockerell, Douglas and Son, 1973.

provenance.p: Given to the Abbey of Bury St Edmunds Abbey of Bury St. Edmunds by Reginald of Denham Reginald of Denham , who is recorded as sacrist c. 1312: 'Reginaldus de Denham sacrista Sancti Eadmundi dedit hunc librum Sancto Eadmundo qui eum alienauerit anathema sit', written within a green framework with grotesque heads (f. 1r).

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on the description provided by Rodney M. Thomson, A descriptive catalogue of the medieval manuscripts at Pembroke College, Cambridge (2022) (used here by kind permission of the author). The introductory summary is adapted from the catalogue entry written by Tessa Webber for the 2005 exhibition The Cambridge Illuminations: Ten centuries of book production in the medieval west, ed. by Paul Binski and Stella Panayotova (supplied by the author).

availability.p: Researchers should note that Pembroke College's western European medieval manuscripts are housed at Cambridge University Library (CUL). Scholars who wish to consult Pembroke College manuscripts should contact the Manuscripts Reading Room at CUL to arrange their visit; all CUL admissions procedures will apply. For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see Joining the Library. For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Manuscripts Reading Room.

msItem.title: Illustrated cycle of the Life of Christ

list.item: Quire 14-1 (front pastedown-folio 2: 2nd leaf, after front pastedown, missing)
Quire 24 (ff. 3-6)

collation.note: First leaf is the front pastedown.

decoNote.p: Twelve full-page framed miniatures, usually divided into three or occasionally two registers, illustrating episodes from the life of Christ. Outlined in ink (same as used for the text) by a single hand, in the style of the 'Alexis Master' of the St Albans Psalter (Hildesheim, Dombibl. St Gotthard MS 1) and New York, Pierpont Morgan Library, MS M.736).

list.item: 1. The Wicked Husbandman
2. Cleansing of the Temple
3. Miracle of the Loaves and Fishes
4. Healing of the man born blind
5. The Woman taken in adultery
6. Raising of Lazarus
7. Parable of the Good Samaritan: a traveller attacked by robbers, a priest and a Levite pass by
8. The Good Samartian tends the traveller's wounds, sets him on his mount and brings him to an inn
9. Zachaeus in the fig tree
10. Christ disputing with the Jews, who stone him
11. Parable of the guest without a wedding garment
12. Entry into Jerusalem
13. The Last Supper
14. Christ washes the disciples' feet
15. The Betrayal
17. Procession to Calvary; Simon bearing the Cross
18. The Crucifixion
19. The Deposition
20. The Entombment; the Jews ask Pilate for a guard
22. The Harrowing of Hell; Noli me tangere
23. The Journey to Emmaus: Cleopas and Peter meet Christ, all dressed as pilgrims; Supper at Emmaus
24. Cleopas and Peter returning from Emmaus; Inredulity of Thomas, who touches Christ's wound
25. Christ seated at a table, four disciples bringing food (fish and honeycomb) (Luke 24:42); Lake Tiberias: Peter walking on the water towards Christ, Christ on the shore, directing the disciples
26. Miraculous draught of fishes, Peter carrying the net ashore; Fish and bread laid on the fire
27. Christ on the mountain, disciples touching his feet (Matthew 28:16-19); Christ appears to the Eleven disciples at table (Mark 16:14)
28. The Ascension
29. The dance of Salome, the beheading of John the Baptist, his head presented on a platter at the banqueting table
30. God and Christ as identical persons, enthroned, in a mandorla between cherubim
31. Pentecost
32. Last Judgement

decoNote.p: Each page containing miniatures was prepared for a border, of which only on those on ff. 1r-3r were filled with paint. The miniatures on 1r-3r were tinted, by a later hand, in blue, green, buff and grey; the rest are sparsely tinted, but those on 5v and 6v left untinted.

collation.note: Last leaf is the rear pastedown

signatures.p: Quire signatures written at the end.

layout.seg: Two columns, 35 lines, ruled in leadpoint, written above top line.

handNote.p: A fine, probably professional, English protogothic bookhand. On f. 182v, a colophon, written by a different hand, names the scribe: 'Nomen Guillelmi cuius manus hoc scripsit uolumen in libro uitae asscribatur.

decoNote.p: Prefaces and each Gospel open with skilfully executed initials painted in shades of blue, green, red, gold, etc. Those to the Gospels contain the Evangelist symbols (ff. 11r, 31v, 70r, 113r).
The initial opening I Peter has St Peter with book and keys (f. 113r).
The other books open with inhabited or foliated initials, very like those in New York, Pierpont Morgan Library. MS M.736 .
The capitula have plain coloured initials and red numbers which are repeated in the margins against each chapter.
Small initials in red, blue and green, mostly plain, some with foliage ornament.
Small initials in the same ink as the text, highlighted in yellow.
